Laurent Bossavit writes:
>
>> The fact that this maxim applies equally to face-to-face games as to
>> email-based games is my reason for claiming that, metaphysically,
>> there's no real difference between the two kinds of games. The
>> metaphysical question is: what is the relationship between the
>> entities defined or referred to by the rules of the game and the
>> physical tokens used to represent the distribution of those entities?
>> Answering that question gives essentially the same picture for
>> Monopoly as it does for Agora, or so I claim. 
>
>I wholeheartedly disagree with that claim, and for several reasons. An obvious 
>one is that nothing distinguishes one P-Note from another, and thus that it 
>seems quite unreasonable to assume that an Entity that we call a P-Note 
>corresponds to any particular set of actual, physical particles. Whereas you 
>can count poker chips, mark them and so on. Agoran Entities have well-defined 
>conceptual boundaries which it would be hopeless to attempt to map to physical 
>boundaries. 

Your point about mapping the conceptual boundaries of Agoran Entities
onto physical boundaries (of some physical medium of representation)
is an interesting one. It is certainly true that numbers stored in
files are not precisely analagous to poker chips: the difference
between '4' and '5' is not a difference between there being four of
something and there being five of something. I suppose that
ultimately the difference between a file which records my VT balance
as 4 and one which records it as 5 is underwritten by the different
ways in which those numbers will be used: I'll be able to cast 4
votes, but not 5. That's only to speak of the difference for us as
game players, of course. There also the matter of the difference it
makes to a computer executing a program, which are ultimately
underwritten by the physical differences in the binary representations 
(and hence in whatever medium of physical memory the computer is
using) of the two numbers. To say more about the differences between
numbers in files and poker chips would be to lead us into the murky
waters of the philosophical literature on the analog/digital and
discrete/continuous distinctions, and my head is hurting enough as it
is.  

However, none of that should blind us to the fact that numbers in
files and poker chips still share the important property of being
physical things. And couldn't the same points you make above be
made with respect to the difference between using poker chips and
using plastic money?

>            Further, some manipulations on Agora Entities correspond to no 
>movement of physical entities at all; such as any automatic change in Currency 
>or other holdings which happens automatically at the start of a Nomic Week.

So what? That's the same as saying that some manipulations of Monopoly
Entities do not correspond to movements of Monopoly money. Depending on
what you mean by 'correspond', that claim is either false, or trivially
true, but uninteresting. Consider the Monopoly rule that a player who
passes Go collects $200. I think that rule is pretty much analogous
to one of our Rules which automatically changes Currency holdings at
the start of a Nomic week, as our Salary Rules used to do before PC.

Of course, simply having the rule there does not magically result
in $200 making its way from the Bank to the Monopoly player: some
person, probably the banker or the player, is going to have to perform
some physical action of transferring plastic money from the bank to
the player who has just passed passed Go. And similarly, simply having
the old Salary Rule (1007/11, I think) did not mean that any numbers
in files actually got changed: the Assessor had to do that. In each
case, the rule licenses some person to perform some physical action
(transferring pastic banknotes, changing numbers in files) which will
count as legal in virtue of the rule's having licensed. So I maintain
the basic similarity between Monopoly and Agora in this respect.

>Or take a hypothetical Rule stating that at the beginning of the Week, a
>number of Kudos from 0 to 10 are transferred from Player A to Player B, the
>number being determined in a non-deterministic manner equiprobably among the
>range of possible choices. This would make the Kudo status of those Players
>unknowable, to be sure, but it would not, nevertheless, make it impossible to
>derive effects upon the Game State that were based on conditions like "the
>probability that Player A has more Kudos than Player B after N Weeks".

Again, so what? We could play a Monopoly variant with a similar rule,
eg instead of receiving $200 when passing Go, a player receives $50,
or $100, $150, or $200, each with a probability of one quarter. If the
actual number of Kudos transferred in your example above is unknowable
(but why is that, precisely? Can't we just roll a dice?), then the amount
of money received by the player from the bank is unknowable, too.
But what objectionable consequences are supposed to follow from this
I don't yet see. No doubt you will soon enlighten me.
