Much of the success Morendil's Mint Manipulation hinges on the naming
issue - the identity of names is the only (potential) connection
between the currencies e minted and the entities created by PC. 

So I checked the use of some terms in PC again.

Four terms occur. "Payment Orders" and "Transfer Orders" are
explicitly defined by the rules, as "an order requiring ..." in 1696
and 1598. Note that these definitions use "order" with a small
"o". This seems to make it clear that in this context "order" (o) is
just the English word you could look up in the dictionary, not an
entity defined by the Agora rules.

In fact, there isn't even a definition of "Order" (capital "O")
anywhere, either. When this term appears alone, it is only as a rather
obvious shorthand for either "Transfer Order" or "Payment Order",
e.g. in 1596, 1598, 1599, 1730 and 1734.

I think this is clear enough now, so Morendil's creating "Orders" as a
separate curency was a kind of overkill. But nevertheless I would like
to propose an amendment of these rules that expands the shorthand with
the full "Transfer" or "Payment" Order as appropriate, if ther are no
serious objections to that.

Kolja A.

