Morendil:
>>The Voting message you send to the Assessor is that body of text.

That's the obvious answer, of course, but I wouldn't dwell on
this point if I liked this answer. Yes, a voting message is a
body of text, and it does have something to do with the connected
implicit TO. 

But "has something to do with" is different from "constitutes".  Ok, a
proposal may be constituted by the text that lists the proposal. But
the TO connected with a vote is created by rule 1442 (and note that
the implicit creation of a TO must be expressly permitted by a rule,
see 1731). In fact, 1442 says that the implicit TO submission is
included in the _act of informing the Assessor of the vote cast_ - it
is not created by a suitable redefinition of terms, as you wrote
earlier:

Morendil:
>>> For the purposes of Currency Transfers a Voting message is declared to
> be legally equivalent to "H. Assessor, please note that I pay for this
> Vote by transferring N VTs to the Bank". This is what 'implicit' Transfer
> Order means. <<

Tu summarize: The possibility to connect items like proposals, rules,
TOs etc with bodies of text has been used in descriptions of the
"entitiness" of such items. Others have mentioned that these items can
cease to be Nomic Entities without ceasing to be connected to bodies
of text; I still insist that items like TOs or POs may be created
implicitly by the _act_ of making or communicating a body of text, but
they are definitely distinct from this body of text. So the connection
"Nomic Entitiness" <--> "Body of text" does not work.

I am not saying this with any particular consequences or applications
in mind, I am just trying to get a clear idea of what is going on. 

Kolja A.

