You could argue that every Payment Order owes its existence to the
Rules because it was created in reponse to a Rule-based requirement
for its creation.  However, I don't think this is a reasonable
argument.  The more I look at and think about the Nomic Entity Rule,
the more convinced I am that there are no Nomic Entities at all,
except perhaps for those entities which are deemed to exist, such as
the Frankenstein Monster.  IMO, Voting Tokens are not a Nomic Entity,
because I could choose to continue to maintain records of Voting
Tokens even if the Rules which "define" them were repealed; their
existence would continue.  I believe Steve has expounded at length on
the actual existence of the myriad of supposedly abstract objects that
comprise Agora, and I am in substantial agreement with Steve on these
issues.  

Of course, under this particular conceptualization of existence, the
entire Nomic Entity concept falls apart as almost wholly devoid of
meaning.  Oh well.

Klaus> I tend to agree - the concept seems very abstract and somewhat
Klaus> unmotivated to a newcomer like me. However, I thought it might have
Klaus> been introduced to close some loopholes you found - in that case a
Klaus> replacement would be needed.

There is, I believe, a deep and fundamental conflict between myself
and several of my fellow Players (most notably, Chuck and Oerjan) as
to the nature of the Rules.  I deny that the Rules have any
generalized power to create, modify, or destroy entities.  In my
opinion, the Rules are limited to creating constraints on the
activities of Players.  The power to create, modify, and destroy
entities lies with Players.  When a Rule states that such and such an
entity is created, it means that this entity has a legal existence,
but not necessarily an actual existence.  Voting Tokens exist because
I and other maintain records of their existence; I do so because I am
required to do so; others do so (or may do so) to insure that I
execute my duties properly and faithfully.  Voting Tokens, and the
records maintained of them, have legal significance because the Rules
specify that they do.  Their existence is not predicated by their
legal significance, and their legal significance is not predicated by
their existence.  It would be most inconvenient to have legal
significance granted to something that did not exist, admittedly, but
it is possible.

Klaus> I would be very happy to follow your concept of looking at the
Klaus> commonsense interpretation of rules, instead of, well,
Klaus> nitpicking and hairsplitting, or put more politely, looking at
Klaus> details, literal meanings and hidden loopholes due to weird
Klaus> rules interpretations. Why aren't you all doing that all the
Klaus> time, anyway?

I don't believe that a "weird rules interpretation" should be admitted
unless all less weird interpretations are demonstrably meaningless or
contradictory.  This is part of what I mean by using "common sense".
This does not in any way rule out hairsplitting or nitpicking, but it
does rule out creating hairs to split and nits to pick out of thin
air.


