> However, none of that should blind us to the fact that numbers in
> files and poker chips still share the important property of being
> physical things.

Except that it is, IMHO, stretching the analogy with poker chips much too far. 
The above is, as you would say, a trivially true but wholly uninteresting 
observation; of course they are.

Your "metaphysical manifesto" has at its core the claim that the relationship 
between Monopoly entities and Monopoly chips is basically the same as the one 
that underlies Nomic entities and an unspecified class of physical 'tokens'. I 
dispute this claim mainly because I see no way that the physical tokens that 
are manipulated in Agora can be meaningfully viewed as equivalent to poker 
chip-like entities, which are largish, discrete, form an easily identified set, 
and so on.

You state that it is equivalent to stand up in a Monopoly game and shout, "I
receive one 100-dollar bill", and post to the PF a message stating "I receive
1 VT from the Bank". Well, that's where I disagree - it's not equivalent,
because the former is a physical manipulation to which the Monopoly tokens are
entirely impervious; just standing around shouting silly things is not going
to move no poker chips around. Whereas _all_ manipulations of physical
entities that are relevant to our playing Agora consist of sending messages of
one sort or another, and it is a very difficult matter to tell which of these 
manipulations are legal and which are not.

