Well, there's the rub. Defining and creating are completely different
things. It's like the difference between me saying "An ice cream sundae is
a dessert consisting of ice cream topped with chocolate sauce, whipped
cream, nuts, and/or other toppings" and actually going downstairs and
dishing myself out one. In this case, I agree with Scott -- the Rules may
very well define something, but they don't just bring it into existence.

>The fact that it is just an artifice of law does not deprive it of
>its existence and therefore, IMO, does not prevent it from being an entity.  

Scott isn't saying that they aren't entities, AFAICT -- he's arguing that
abstract things can be entities whether or not the Rules describe them or not.



