Naaah, get real - considered as an economic game, Agora doesn't even approach
the complexity of Monopoly. The Rules governing the recordkeeping are more
complex, mostly because they're rooted in the Rules for Currencies, Officers,
CFJs, &c. - but there are far fewer events in Agora that cause transfer than 
there are in Monopoly.

> Should you successfully convince the Recordkeepor that you should actually
> receive that 1 VT, even if the Rules don't say so, you *will.* In Monopoly,
> if you convince the other players that the rules would have given you that
> $100, even if in reality they don't, you still would get the $100. 

I certainly don't agree with that. I don't only have to convince the Assessor,
I have to convince every Player, plus everyone who might at some future time be
a Player and has access to the game's records, and also I have to cover my
tracks entirely and eradicate every trace of the actual, legal, Game State
from every file wherein it's recorded - and these files are duplicated all
over the world.

Steve would probably say that there is it merely a difference of magnitude
between the task of illegally stealing one VT from the Bank and stealing $100
from a Monopoly Bank, but I disagree - precisely because in Monopoly, the 
'records' are the chips and notes themselves, and there is IMHO a world of 
difference between large-scale, discrete objects such as chips and notes and 
widespread, fuzzy collections of small objects such as the one that comprise 
our 'records' of the Game State.

